               <p>ELIZA FRANCIS. I am a widow. On the 29th of April the prisoner was my lodger; I had seen the shawl in the closet a few hours before it was missed - I found it at the pawnbroker's.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280529-157-person903">
                  JAMES 
                  MOODY
               <interp inst="t18280529-157-person903" type="surname" value="MOODY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280529-157-person903" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280529-157-person903" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a pawnbroker. I have a shawl, pawned by the prisoner, on the 29th of April.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. PHILLIPS. Q. Had you known him before? A. No; it was between seven and eight o'clock in the evening - the shutters were closed, but there was plenty of light from the gas.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280529-157-person904">
                  HENRY 
                  RICHARD BUCKERIDGE
               <interp inst="t18280529-157-person904" type="surname" value="RICHARD BUCKERIDGE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280529-157-person904" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280529-157-person904" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an officer. I was fetched by a person named Hill, and took the prisoner in Arthur-street; I brought him to the Turk's Head public-house, and there he saw the prosecutrix; he at first denied knowing her, but afterwards he told me if I would let him go he would give me a guinea and redeem the shawl.</p>
               <p>ELIZA FRANCIS. I know the shawl, for it has never been out of the paper - it is new; I have no mark on it, but the corner of the paper is torn off.</p>
